BAE, Iberdrola, PPR, Societe Generale: European Equity Preview

-- B y   W h i t n e y   K i s l i n g
-- 
2011-05-25T04:01:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-24/bae-iberdrola-ppr-societe-generale-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index rose 0.2 percent to 275.39. The
Stoxx 50 Index advanced 0.2 percent to 2,580.23. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, gained 0.3
percent to 2,801.27.       Actividades de Construccion y Servicios SA (ACS SM): Grupo
Dragados SA, a unit of  Spain ’s biggest construction company, is
offering to increase the interest margin on a loan signed in
2009 in order to extend its maturity by two years, according to
two people with knowledge of the situation. The shares gained
0.8 percent to 32.19 euros.  BAE Systems Plc (BA/)  : Europe’s largest defense company
said it agreed to sell its composite structures business in
Brea,  California , to EnCore Composites Holdings Inc. The shares
fell 0.5 percent to 328.7 pence.  Cofinimmo (COFB)  SA:  Belgium ’s biggest real-estate
investment fund said it will issue 330,246 new shares, raising
31 million euros ($43.8 million) as 37.7 percent of its current
shareholders opted for a stock dividend. Cofinimmo rose less
than 0.1 percent to 97.03 euros.  Electricite de  France  SA (EDF FP): Europe’s biggest power
producer said it will focus development on nuclear energy even
after the disaster at Fukushima in  Japan . The shares fell 0.4
percent to 28.27 euros.  Iberdrola SA (IBE)  : The Spanish power company which
counts ACS as its biggest stakeholder will propose to
shareholders this week that it pay its ordinary 2010 dividend of
3 euro cents per share on July 13. The shares rose less than 0.1
percent to 5.97 euros.  PPR (PP)  SA: The luxury-goods producer hired Rothschild
& Cie. to arrange financing that could be used to fund a
private-equity buyout of online retailer Redcats, according to
two people with knowledge of the matter. The shares rose 2.3
percent to 117.70 euros.  Societe Generale (GLE)  SA: France’s second-largest bank
reiterated its 2012 financial targets, including reaching 6
billion euros in annual profit next year. The shares fell 0.2
percent to 41.23 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Whitney Kisling in New York at 
 wkisling@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
